                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d382">
                <head>382. Telegram 1047 From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to
                    the <gloss type="to">Consulate General in Dacca</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d382fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 627,
                        Country Files, Middle East, Pakistan, Vol. IX, Jan-31 Aug 72. Secret;
                        Priority; Nodis. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName>,
                        cleared by <persName corresp="#p_ETLJ1">Eliot</persName>, and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>. Repeated to Calcutta,
                        Islamabad, and New Delhi.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d382fn2">Secretary of State <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> instructed Consul General <persName
                            corresp="#p_SHD1">Spivack</persName> to avoid further contact with
                        Bangladesh representatives.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1972-01-04"
                        >January 4, 1972, 2232Z</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>For <persName corresp="#p_SHD1">Spivack</persName> from Secretary</p>
                <p>In view of sensitivity and fluidity of situation you should seek to avoid further
                    contact with Bangla Desh reps. If Bangla Desh reps seek appointment with you,
                    you should seek instructions from Department.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
